00:07:25.162 --> 00:07:27.530
Hi, thank you, JD, for
your kind introduction.

00:07:27.530 --> 00:07:29.280
So I think it might
be helpful to give you

00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:33.710
a bit of a background on how I
got involved in this project.

00:07:33.710 --> 00:07:40.540
So I got frustrated
with events in Africa,

00:07:40.540 --> 00:07:44.780
and I think the easiest thing
to do is criticize, right?

00:07:44.780 --> 00:07:49.160
And most of the criticism is
often leveled at our leaders.

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:54.240
I came to the view that one,
as an instrument of change,

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:58.090
criticism is actually a
spectacularly blunt one.

00:07:58.090 --> 00:08:03.330
And secondly, I came to the view
that leadership, if you will,

00:08:03.330 --> 00:08:07.750
the knowledge that really
comes to mind is will.

00:08:07.750 --> 00:08:10.810
So you have government,
the civil society,

00:08:10.810 --> 00:08:12.100
and there is business.

00:08:12.100 --> 00:08:15.046
So the fact that most
governments in Africa

00:08:15.046 --> 00:08:16.420
don't live up to
the expectations

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:20.050
should not preclude us from
being change agents in business

00:08:20.050 --> 00:08:21.860
and civil society.

00:08:21.860 --> 00:08:24.900
And one of my early
inspirations was from Nollywood

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:27.900
in Nigeria, which
by some estimates

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:32.294
is the second or third
largest employer in Nigeria.

00:08:32.294 --> 00:08:33.210
So I grew up in Ghana.

00:08:33.210 --> 00:08:34.274
So I had the--

00:08:34.274 --> 00:08:38.260
I saw Nollywood basically
become an economic engine out

00:08:38.260 --> 00:08:39.730
of nothing.

00:08:39.730 --> 00:08:42.669
And if you studied the
industry quite well,

00:08:42.669 --> 00:08:47.230
most of the people that
are actually driving change

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:50.030
have very little formal
education in filmmaking.

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:52.900
But they're mostly, in
Nigerian parlance, hustlers

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:55.630
who have been able to
create opportunities,

00:08:55.630 --> 00:08:57.760
and Nollywood has
been able to thrive

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:00.180
in spite of an
ineffectual government

00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:02.200
apparatus in Nigeria.

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:06.050
So my challenge to people,
like myself with fancy degrees

00:09:06.050 --> 00:09:07.710
and work titles, was, look at--

00:09:07.710 --> 00:09:10.120
Nollywood is getting things
done in spite of the fact

00:09:10.120 --> 00:09:12.507
that governance in
Nigeria is not optimal,

00:09:12.507 --> 00:09:14.590
in spite of the fact that
most them lack training.

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:16.580
What can we do?

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:18.820
So we took that
conversation further

00:09:18.820 --> 00:09:21.760
by forming an investment
platform called

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:23.600
Diaspora Capital.

00:09:23.600 --> 00:09:27.180
[INAUDIBLE] Citizen Capital from
the African diasporan community

00:09:27.180 --> 00:09:30.850
have been able to mobilize
quite a bit of funds, invested

00:09:30.850 --> 00:09:34.000
in countries in Ghana,
Liberia, Zambia,

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.490
and most recently, in Penang.

00:09:36.490 --> 00:09:39.700
Along the way, in spite
of your best efforts,

00:09:39.700 --> 00:09:45.010
we run into a number of issues
that affected our ability

00:09:45.010 --> 00:09:45.940
to do business.

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:49.150
So I was working on
chronicling the challenges

00:09:49.150 --> 00:09:52.180
that we face as investors
and also the businesses

00:09:52.180 --> 00:09:54.870
we invest in in doing
business in Africa.

00:09:54.870 --> 00:10:00.070
And the goal was to convert
the lessons into an easily

00:10:00.070 --> 00:10:03.100
digestible visual format--

00:10:03.100 --> 00:10:06.880
i.e. a documentary-- with
a case study on the Congo,

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:09.850
and that is when I run
into JD and his team.

00:10:09.850 --> 00:10:12.220
And they already had their
well-developed product

00:10:12.220 --> 00:10:15.610
so I felt it probably would
make sense to work with them

00:10:15.610 --> 00:10:18.530
as opposed to trying
to reinvent the wheel.

00:10:18.530 --> 00:10:21.310
So does my involvement, and one
thing I also want to emphasize

00:10:21.310 --> 00:10:23.500
is I'm not from the Congo.

00:10:23.500 --> 00:10:25.259
So the question
is why the Congo?

00:10:25.259 --> 00:10:26.800
Well, first of all,
I'd like to thank

00:10:26.800 --> 00:10:28.300
[INAUDIBLE] and the
team from Google

00:10:28.300 --> 00:10:31.280
for giving us this
opportunity to be here.

00:10:31.280 --> 00:10:34.730
We have tried to run this by
a number of organizations,

00:10:34.730 --> 00:10:38.590
including African focus
organizations, and some of them

00:10:38.590 --> 00:10:42.250
have flat out told us they
didn't see any alignment,

00:10:42.250 --> 00:10:46.240
which I personally have
found quite perplexing.

00:10:46.240 --> 00:10:49.270
Even from a purely
humanitarian perspective,

00:10:49.270 --> 00:10:53.800
5.4 million people have
died from the war in Congo.

00:10:53.800 --> 00:10:56.814
This is, to put it
in context, about 2/3

00:10:56.814 --> 00:10:58.480
of the population of
New York or London,

00:10:58.480 --> 00:11:02.170
bigger than the
population of Norway.

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:04.830
These Black Lives Matter, too.

00:11:04.830 --> 00:11:06.505
The second point
I'd like to raise

00:11:06.505 --> 00:11:10.825
is the fact that Congo
is too big to fail.

00:11:10.825 --> 00:11:12.700
When I was in grad
school, one of the lessons

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:16.510
I learned was the best
predictor of war in a country

00:11:16.510 --> 00:11:17.990
is war next door.

00:11:17.990 --> 00:11:22.630
And looking at the Congo,
it's destabilizing forces

00:11:22.630 --> 00:11:26.080
have led to nine other
countries been plunged

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:29.788
into one conflict or the other.

00:11:29.788 --> 00:11:31.870
The other point I'd
like to raise also

00:11:31.870 --> 00:11:33.760
is that strategically
speaking, I

00:11:33.760 --> 00:11:35.470
would argue that
Congo is probably

00:11:35.470 --> 00:11:38.260
the most strategically
important,

00:11:38.260 --> 00:11:41.200
the most strategically important
country in Africa, at least

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:42.049
throughout history.

00:11:42.049 --> 00:11:43.840
I mean, if you look at
the main events that

00:11:43.840 --> 00:11:47.050
have shaped our
global economy, Congo

00:11:47.050 --> 00:11:51.240
has had a say starting from
the Industrial Revolution.

00:11:51.240 --> 00:11:56.136
The rubber that was used to
power the Industrial Revolution

00:11:56.136 --> 00:11:58.810
was sourced from the
forest in the Congo.

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:01.000
Looking at the
First World War, 75%

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:05.024
of the brass casings
that came from the war

00:12:05.024 --> 00:12:06.190
were sourced from the Congo.

00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:09.280
Going down to Second
World War, the uranium up

00:12:09.280 --> 00:12:11.290
to today in the [INAUDIBLE]
and cobalt that are

00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:14.550
used to power mobile telephony.

00:12:14.550 --> 00:12:18.280
So the misfortune with
the Congo is its knack

00:12:18.280 --> 00:12:20.230
for producing the
right resources at most

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:23.560
critical times have lead
to a bit of a scramble

00:12:23.560 --> 00:12:27.720
for its resources, starting
with the European colonialists

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:31.440
to the actors in the Cold War to
most recently local insurgency

00:12:31.440 --> 00:12:32.340
groups.

00:12:32.340 --> 00:12:35.640
And lastly, the reason why I
think the Congo is important

00:12:35.640 --> 00:12:38.850
and why we should
all care is I think

00:12:38.850 --> 00:12:41.940
there is an existential crises,
not just in Congo, but in most

00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:44.760
of Africa, which
is a lack of jobs.

00:12:44.760 --> 00:12:47.850
There aren't too many
examples of countries

00:12:47.850 --> 00:12:52.840
moving from grinding poverty to
emerging or developed countries

00:12:52.840 --> 00:12:56.190
status without having
a manufacturing base.

00:12:56.190 --> 00:12:58.625
And the reason why
Africa's industrial hub

00:12:58.625 --> 00:13:00.750
hasn't taken off, in spite
of the fact that we have

00:13:00.750 --> 00:13:03.390
a number of advantages,
is due to the fact

00:13:03.390 --> 00:13:06.690
that we don't have
access to electricity

00:13:06.690 --> 00:13:08.130
at an affordable price.

00:13:08.130 --> 00:13:09.870
And Congo has the resources--

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:13.110
I mean, the Congo River
itself has a potential

00:13:13.110 --> 00:13:16.770
to generate up to 100,000
megawatts of electricity.

00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:22.260
That's 13% of the world's
hydroelectric potential.

00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:24.060
And the beauty with
the Congo River

00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:27.720
is, unlike most river
basins in Africa, which

00:13:27.720 --> 00:13:33.660
tend to dry out during the
dry season, the Congo River,

00:13:33.660 --> 00:13:36.970
the [INAUDIBLE] basin sits
north and south of the equator.

00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:38.880
So at any given
time, a part of it

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:41.910
experiences the rainy season.

00:13:41.910 --> 00:13:44.670
So the only way we could
realize Congo's potential

00:13:44.670 --> 00:13:47.640
is to create this environment
to bring the best out

00:13:47.640 --> 00:13:49.350
of it and its people.

00:13:49.350 --> 00:13:50.666
Thank you.

00:13:50.666 --> 00:13:51.790
JD STIER: Thank you, Kwame.

