been learned about today.

00:26:30.150 --> 00:26:32.580
In the film, they
really broke down--

00:26:32.580 --> 00:26:35.760
which is a very complex sector
and one of the largest mining

00:26:35.760 --> 00:26:37.200
sectors on earth--

00:26:37.200 --> 00:26:39.690
into the east of Congo
and the south of Congo.

00:26:39.690 --> 00:26:42.150
And as you heard,
the human atrocities

00:26:42.150 --> 00:26:44.250
are unparalleled in the east.

00:26:44.250 --> 00:26:48.090
Conservative estimates say
that over 6 million people have

00:26:48.090 --> 00:26:50.400
died since the 1996
war in the east,

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:55.200
and many experts agree
it's many millions more.

00:26:55.200 --> 00:26:58.391
There's myriad armed groups,
dozens of semi-autonomous armed

00:26:58.391 --> 00:26:58.890
groups.

00:26:58.890 --> 00:27:01.380
Yes, a few of the biggest,
most well-funded groups

00:27:01.380 --> 00:27:03.210
are Rwandan backed.

00:27:03.210 --> 00:27:05.880
Uganda plays a role
in that as well,

00:27:05.880 --> 00:27:08.760
and the Congolese elites
have a role in some

00:27:08.760 --> 00:27:10.620
of those groups as well.

00:27:10.620 --> 00:27:13.920
In that melee of
competing armed groups,

00:27:13.920 --> 00:27:17.230
the humans on the ground are the
ones paying the price for that.

00:27:17.230 --> 00:27:21.090
They use sexual violence as a
tactic of war, intimidation,

00:27:21.090 --> 00:27:24.630
child soldier recruitment,
and other human atrocities,

00:27:24.630 --> 00:27:28.380
mass atrocities, to control
those mineral areas.

00:27:28.380 --> 00:27:31.290
Now the human rights
push originating

00:27:31.290 --> 00:27:34.560
in Congo with youth movement
leaders that I mentioned--

00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:38.845
LUCHA is the French acronym
"fight for change"--

00:27:38.845 --> 00:27:40.620
it is an entity that's
really been leading

00:27:40.620 --> 00:27:44.550
the push for transparency
and for better

00:27:44.550 --> 00:27:45.630
governance on the ground.

00:27:45.630 --> 00:27:49.650
They've been joined by
Congolese living in the diaspora

00:27:49.650 --> 00:27:53.330
and international
citizens in solidarity,

00:27:53.330 --> 00:27:56.100
and this is where this
large push since 2010,

00:27:56.100 --> 00:27:59.040
2011, has resulted in some
of the world's major tech

00:27:59.040 --> 00:28:01.200
companies taking aim.

00:28:01.200 --> 00:28:05.370
And by having Intel, Motorola
Solutions, and others actually

00:28:05.370 --> 00:28:08.490
go visit with
mineral mining rights

00:28:08.490 --> 00:28:12.000
associations and Congolese
civil society organizations,

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:13.830
whereas five years
ago, there were

00:28:13.830 --> 00:28:17.040
no certified mines
in the east, there

00:28:17.040 --> 00:28:21.480
are now many dozens of
certified mines in the east.

00:28:21.480 --> 00:28:24.370
I was there in January
with our film team,

00:28:24.370 --> 00:28:28.530
and we visited one of the
largest mines in eastern Congo.

00:28:28.530 --> 00:28:31.200
There's a minimum wage,
there's safety requirements,

00:28:31.200 --> 00:28:33.270
there are labor requirements,
there are no more

00:28:33.270 --> 00:28:35.280
children working in
the mines, and you're

00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:38.910
seeing this type of operation
spreading in the east.

00:28:38.910 --> 00:28:41.160
And it's happening because
there's solidarity,

00:28:41.160 --> 00:28:43.350
because you have some large
purchasers in the West,

00:28:43.350 --> 00:28:46.740
like yourselves,
joining a coalition,

00:28:46.740 --> 00:28:50.280
joining conversation,
Congolese-led solutions

00:28:50.280 --> 00:28:51.460
on the ground.

00:28:51.460 --> 00:28:54.240
There is no shortage of
Congolese entrepreneurs

00:28:54.240 --> 00:28:59.550
that want to do sustainable
long term and safe business.

00:28:59.550 --> 00:29:01.350
It's the corruption
and the armed groups

00:29:01.350 --> 00:29:02.400
that get in the way.

00:29:02.400 --> 00:29:04.680
But when you have a critical
mass of stakeholders

00:29:04.680 --> 00:29:07.560
come together, the
unity is strong enough

00:29:07.560 --> 00:29:10.800
where they can pilot
and now flourish

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:12.540
with conflict-free models.

00:29:12.540 --> 00:29:15.910
This extends beyond
mining in the east.

00:29:15.910 --> 00:29:18.180
There's Congo coffee
peace project.

00:29:18.180 --> 00:29:22.080
A former rebel commander,
General [? Cassango ?] is now

00:29:22.080 --> 00:29:28.800
a part of a 2,500 person-strong
fair trade coffee operation,

00:29:28.800 --> 00:29:31.560
which fills up a large, Masisi--

00:29:31.560 --> 00:29:35.520
area of the Masisi
province north of Goma.

00:29:35.520 --> 00:29:39.780
This is 2,500 men that used to
be in local armed groups that

00:29:39.780 --> 00:29:43.860
are now all working in the
coffee trade, fair trade coffee

00:29:43.860 --> 00:29:44.370
trade.

00:29:44.370 --> 00:29:47.690
There's almost no violence and
no theft in Masisi anymore,

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:50.530
and everybody has a
reliable full time income.

00:29:50.530 --> 00:29:53.130
And so this push
and really the need

00:29:53.130 --> 00:29:55.350
for some international
solidarity--

00:29:55.350 --> 00:29:57.840
and not just civil society
leaders and business

00:29:57.840 --> 00:30:00.060
leaders like ourselves--
but corporations

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:05.010
and powerful entities showing an
interest changes the dynamics.

00:30:05.010 --> 00:30:07.090
I remember getting a call
from Fidel Bafilemba,

00:30:07.090 --> 00:30:10.140
a prominent activist
featured throughout the film.

00:30:10.140 --> 00:30:12.720
One of the leading experts
on mining and transparency

00:30:12.720 --> 00:30:17.340
in the east gave me a call
shortly after the Intel

00:30:17.340 --> 00:30:20.730
presentation at the Consumer
Electronics Show in January

00:30:20.730 --> 00:30:24.090
2013 said that he got a
call from one of the most

00:30:24.090 --> 00:30:28.700
notorious armed commanders
in Congo and said, Fidel,

00:30:28.700 --> 00:30:31.020
I know you're working with
these people in the West

00:30:31.020 --> 00:30:33.180
and these companies.

00:30:33.180 --> 00:30:35.010
If someone wanted to
hire me and my men

00:30:35.010 --> 00:30:36.660
to be like a
security contractor,

00:30:36.660 --> 00:30:38.500
we're open for that.

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:40.920
And so even from
who we would want

00:30:40.920 --> 00:30:42.750
to call the bad guys
of which there's

00:30:42.750 --> 00:30:44.980
nothing that simple and
nothing black and white,

00:30:44.980 --> 00:30:49.840
and from many child soldiers
and army commanders and soldiers

00:30:49.840 --> 00:30:54.310
that I've met and gotten to
know their stories pretty well,

00:30:54.310 --> 00:30:56.980
a pretty common scenario
is your mother is raped,

00:30:56.980 --> 00:30:59.830
your father is killed,
and you're recruited.

00:30:59.830 --> 00:31:02.530
And so when we take a
look back at the influence

00:31:02.530 --> 00:31:05.260
and the corruption, it's just
not black and white and good

00:31:05.260 --> 00:31:06.220
guys and bad guys.

00:31:06.220 --> 00:31:08.560
It's much more complex
and nuanced than that,

00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:12.700
and the one uniting factor and
a real strong reason for hope

00:31:12.700 --> 00:31:13.660
is development.

00:31:13.660 --> 00:31:15.760
It's business development,
it's transparency,

00:31:15.760 --> 00:31:20.410
and it's having a reliable, safe
way to make your livelihood.

00:31:20.410 --> 00:31:23.020
And the appetite is so strong.

00:31:23.020 --> 00:31:26.500
Now it gets to the other part
of my answer to your question,

00:31:26.500 --> 00:31:29.380
and that's kind of some of
the good news in the east.

00:31:29.380 --> 00:31:32.680
The south, where Bloomberg
analysts referred

00:31:32.680 --> 00:31:36.310
to as the real money, the
billion dollar deals, that's

00:31:36.310 --> 00:31:38.000
handled by Kabila
and his regime,

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:40.900
Gecamines, the state
mining industry.

00:31:40.900 --> 00:31:43.150
Very little signs
of progress, and I'd

00:31:43.150 --> 00:31:44.550
just almost love to say, no.

00:31:44.550 --> 00:31:46.420
There's no progress.

00:31:46.420 --> 00:31:49.960
Global Witness, a British-based
transparency organization

00:31:49.960 --> 00:31:52.060
that you can find
through our website,

00:31:52.060 --> 00:31:56.770
continues to document instances
of multimillion dollar bribes

00:31:56.770 --> 00:31:59.930
from Glencore, which
is based in the UK.

00:31:59.930 --> 00:32:02.350
If you look in, some of
their major shareholders

00:32:02.350 --> 00:32:05.500
are our own American-based
retirement funds

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:08.090
that we select for our 401ks.

00:32:08.090 --> 00:32:10.540
There's a lot of pressure
we could put, especially

00:32:10.540 --> 00:32:12.700
through shareholders,
on Glencore.

00:32:12.700 --> 00:32:15.490
Glencore is one of the major
financiers of the Kabila

00:32:15.490 --> 00:32:20.080
regime, his family, maintaining
the status quo of corruption.

00:32:20.080 --> 00:32:21.700
Congo-- in just a
couple of years,

00:32:21.700 --> 00:32:24.460
looking at just a few
deals, the Congolese people

00:32:24.460 --> 00:32:27.820
lost over a billion
dollars to corrupt deals

00:32:27.820 --> 00:32:29.650
whereas President
Kabila would personally

00:32:29.650 --> 00:32:32.230
get a bribe in the
millions of dollars

00:32:32.230 --> 00:32:35.530
and then sell off Congolese
mining concessions

00:32:35.530 --> 00:32:37.720
at billions under market value.

00:32:37.720 --> 00:32:39.850
That practice continues
today, and that's

00:32:39.850 --> 00:32:42.040
what many experts agree
is the reason why he's

00:32:42.040 --> 00:32:45.100
ignoring the Constitution
and is relatively immune

00:32:45.100 --> 00:32:46.810
from international pressure.

00:32:46.810 --> 00:32:48.760
He has a virtual blank check.

00:32:48.760 --> 00:32:51.190
And that's all connected
to our mining industry

00:32:51.190 --> 00:32:53.320
and the minerals that we
rely on in our industries

00:32:53.320 --> 00:32:54.620
and in our lives.

00:32:54.620 --> 00:32:57.130
And so while public pressure
has improved some conditions

00:32:57.130 --> 00:33:00.190
in the east and there an
increasing number of certified

00:33:00.190 --> 00:33:03.610
conflict-free minds and other
entrepreneurial ventures

00:33:03.610 --> 00:33:07.120
in the east, the state
as a whole and the sector

00:33:07.120 --> 00:33:09.340
in the south, where the
real money has been made,

00:33:09.340 --> 00:33:11.627
I think is the thing that
we need to continue to focus

00:33:11.627 --> 00:33:13.960
on, and we're going to continue
to advocate for and look

00:33:13.960 --> 00:33:17.050
for increasing partnerships
for, but really put pressure

00:33:17.050 --> 00:33:19.060
on the Western
mining companies--

00:33:19.060 --> 00:33:21.280
Glencore chief among them--

00:33:21.280 --> 00:33:23.150
to end their support
of the Kabila regime

00:33:23.150 --> 00:33:27.640
and for really being the
root of corruption in Congo.

00:33:27.640 --> 00:33:29.860
KWAME MARFO: Quickly,
so within a continent,

00:33:29.860 --> 00:33:31.960
I know a number of countries--

00:33:31.960 --> 00:33:34.690
I know Ghana, for example--

00:33:34.690 --> 00:33:37.950
recently discovered oil
and has been exporting.

00:33:37.950 --> 00:33:41.530
In terms of petroleum bills,
we actually got a bit of help

00:33:41.530 --> 00:33:44.845
from Norway in terms of
building up our capacity.

00:33:44.845 --> 00:33:48.530
So on paper, we have some
quote "best practices."

00:33:48.530 --> 00:33:51.880
But in practice,
[INAUDIBLE] events in Ghana,

00:33:51.880 --> 00:33:53.260
we're doing really well.

00:33:53.260 --> 00:33:55.060
GDP growing at 8%.

00:33:55.060 --> 00:33:57.880
For five years, we discovered
a new and economy imploded.

00:33:57.880 --> 00:34:00.550
So when the rubber
did hit a tire,

00:34:00.550 --> 00:34:06.880
the resource infrastructure
has been deemed to be 110.

00:34:06.880 --> 00:34:10.330
I know countries like Botswana
has done a pretty good job.

00:34:10.330 --> 00:34:13.750
Senegal recently
discovered large deposits

00:34:13.750 --> 00:34:15.790
of natural resources,
and there's

00:34:15.790 --> 00:34:17.110
conversation around doing that.

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:22.050
Outside of Africa,
I know it was--

00:34:22.050 --> 00:34:24.580
so with the last
US administration,

00:34:24.580 --> 00:34:27.699
so during the passage of the
Dodd-Frank Financial Reform

00:34:27.699 --> 00:34:28.510
Bill--

00:34:28.510 --> 00:34:32.650
so there's a provision in
it which basically requests

00:34:32.650 --> 00:34:37.120
that companies doing mining
to publish what they pay,

00:34:37.120 --> 00:34:40.120
which is designed to
bring transparency.

00:34:40.120 --> 00:34:45.280
And US taking that initiative
led the EU and Canada, which

00:34:45.280 --> 00:34:48.550
I believe collectively
make up 75% of revenue

00:34:48.550 --> 00:34:51.820
generated within the
sector, to also raise

00:34:51.820 --> 00:34:54.489
the bar for companies
operating in these regions

00:34:54.489 --> 00:34:59.300
to publish what they pay to
expose any corrupt practices.

00:34:59.300 --> 00:35:01.210
Unfortunately, the
new administration

00:35:01.210 --> 00:35:06.910
here in the United States is
looking at reversing this bill.

00:35:06.910 --> 00:35:09.940
The good thing is I think this
went through Congress so it

00:35:09.940 --> 00:35:12.910
cannot be unwound through
an executive action.

00:35:12.910 --> 00:35:14.470
It would have to go
through Congress.

00:35:14.470 --> 00:35:16.270
But we know the current
Secretary of State

00:35:16.270 --> 00:35:18.740
has been in favor of
this bill, a good number

00:35:18.740 --> 00:35:22.640
of the Senators on the other
side of the political spectrum

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:24.260
were on the same
side as the President

00:35:24.260 --> 00:35:27.130
now so not very much in favor.

00:35:27.130 --> 00:35:31.200
So I guess we're in
watch and see mode.

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:33.250
We also had a
conversation with the UN,

00:35:33.250 --> 00:35:35.970
UNDP, about three
weeks ago, and there

00:35:35.970 --> 00:35:38.760
is a conversation around the
screening this documentary

00:35:38.760 --> 00:35:40.970
and what the UN is doing.

00:35:40.970 --> 00:35:43.270
And part of what really
piqued their interest

00:35:43.270 --> 00:35:44.940
with this documentary
is they've been

00:35:44.940 --> 00:35:48.220
spend a lot of time working with
countries that have recently

00:35:48.220 --> 00:35:51.880
discovered natural resources to
help build up their capacity.

00:35:51.880 --> 00:35:56.890
That said, I think most of
the current bills in place

00:35:56.890 --> 00:36:00.280
have been largely focused
on natural resources

00:36:00.280 --> 00:36:02.680
and how to make
the most out of it.

00:36:02.680 --> 00:36:05.830
Unfortunately, I
think the challenge

00:36:05.830 --> 00:36:09.880
and why I think these
bills aren't really working

00:36:09.880 --> 00:36:12.910
is the focus has been
largely on the resources

00:36:12.910 --> 00:36:17.180
and how to get the best
price, how to negotiate.

00:36:17.180 --> 00:36:20.390
My view-- and this
is one thing we've

00:36:20.390 --> 00:36:22.390
been working with
JD to get across--

00:36:22.390 --> 00:36:25.360
is Africa's most valuable
resources are not

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:27.350
what lies underneath the Earth.

00:36:27.350 --> 00:36:28.780
They're hiding in plain sight.

00:36:28.780 --> 00:36:30.470
It's just people.

00:36:30.470 --> 00:36:33.520
So to the extent that we could
engage policy makers to channel

00:36:33.520 --> 00:36:36.430
these resources towards
investing in the human capital,

00:36:36.430 --> 00:36:38.920
I think that will be
the right way to go.

00:36:38.920 --> 00:36:40.420
So most of the
current conversations

00:36:40.420 --> 00:36:44.380
I've been around setting
up sovereign wealth funds,

00:36:44.380 --> 00:36:48.400
trying to find ways to
increase the bargaining powers,

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:49.990
and it's all a bit
resource-focused.

00:36:49.990 --> 00:36:53.140
I think if we could channel
that discussion away from,

00:36:53.140 --> 00:36:56.230
you know, to
investing in people I

00:36:56.230 --> 00:37:00.490
think that can drive
the change and lead

00:37:00.490 --> 00:37:04.510
to more sustainable
growth on the continent.

